3. Scale up

User types https://www.foobar.com in the browser.
DNS sends the request to the load balancer.
The load balancer sends the request to one of the web servers.
The web server sends the request to the application server.
The application server processes the request and gets data from the database.

Infrastructure:

User
  |
DNS: www.foobar.com
  |
Load Balancer 1 (HAProxy)
Load Balancer 2 (HAProxy - cluster)
  |
  |-----------|
  v           v
Web Server 1  Web Server 2 (Nginx)
      |
Application Server
      |
Database Server (MySQL)

Why we added a second load balancer:
We added another load balancer to avoid single point of failure.
If one load balancer goes down, the other one will still work.

Why we added another server:
We added more servers to handle more traffic.
This helps the system scale and support more users.

Why we split components:

Web server:
Handles HTTP requests and serves static files.

Application server:
Runs the application logic and processes requests.

Database server:
Stores and manages data.

Splitting them is better because:
Each part can scale separately.
For example, if we need more performance, we can upgrade only the database or only the web servers.

Application server vs web server:

Web server:
Handles requests from users and serves static content.

Application server:
Handles logic, runs code, and talks to the database.

This design is better because it is more flexible and easier to scale.
